content.description: Start on the right side of the overhang with a good jug. Climb left along the lip to a tough mantle onto the slab. Will probably get easier with traffic as it was dirty as hell when I climbed it.
content.location: From the right end of Alphabet wall, follow the trail for Givler's Dome etc past the green sign and uphill. Once past the steepest sections, about 5 minutes up the trail, break right across a small gully and follow small cairns for 2-3 minutes. Look for a small bench with a dark overhang a few feet above the trail, this is the spot.

content.description: This climb is worth doing if you frequent the area plenty, but otherwise I wouldn't do it because of how dirty the top-out slab is (it's still doable, but it's sketch smearing on dirt). Sit start matched on a low right facing sidepull. Move up to slopers in the seam, traversing right until the seam starts thinning and you have good slopers overhead. Prepare for the crux, a physical and technical mantle. Top-out via the VDirty slab.
content.protection: 2-3 pads to protect the traverse, 1 or more for the slab top-out (for confidence)
content.location: From the parking, walk up the street 10 feet or so and follow the trail that is across the street. After 15 feet of following the trail, this boulder will be on your left, just at the base of the wall before you.

content.description:
Climb straight up on "juggy huecos and pockets." Although it's exhilarating and airy because of the sloping landing into the abyss below, there's nothing too special about the movement on this line. Sit on the top ledge and chill out for a bit to take in the view. Traverse left and then down the crack to get down. Â If you're a pebble wrestler like me, then the down climb will be harder than going up.

This one is hard to protect, but it's very easy. A pad for the up climb and a pad for the down climb may boost confidence, but falling is not an option in the first place.
content.location: Hike up around the left side of Alphabet Wall, just slightly down canyon and across the street from the parking. You'll see a little amphitheater and an obvious line that faces up the canyon.
